## Shards in Your Appetizers?

If you thought the danger of biting into glass was relegated to thrillers or dramas, think again. Ajinomoto Foods North America Inc. is under fire for recalling multiple frozen food items due to the presence of glass shards, according to a recent FDA report. From green gyoza to shrimp fried rice, these products have been reportedly contaminated with fragments measuring up to 3 cm long. Yes, you read that right, three whole centimeters. Ajinomoto's response includes the recall of a series of items including Trader Joe's Vegetable Fried Rice and their own branded products like Tai Pei Shrimp Fried Rice. Investigations are underway to determine the source of the contamination.

## When a Pickle Isn't Just a Pickle

Mangalm LLC has issued a recall for a range of their imported pickles, citing a high level of erucic acid from mustard oil as the reason. While mustard oil is a common ingredient in Indian cuisine, it has its critics in the food safety world. The products, such as Tops GOLD Stuffed Red Chilli Pickle and Green Chilli Pickle, hail from India and were flagged for potential health concerns. Erucic acid, in high concentrations, can impact cardiac health, hence the classification of this recall as Class II.

## Steel Springs in Dairy? Really?

Albertsons Companies LLC made it to the recall list yet again, with a peculiar incident involving steel springs. Their Lucerne 2% Cottage Cheese was found to contain metal fragments, posing a potential choking hazard. The recurring recalls from Albertsons hint at systemic issues that remain unaddressed, contributing to their dismal performance in food safety over the years.

## The Numbers Don't Lie

This year alone, we've seen 286 food recalls, with 83 classified as Class I, indicating a reasonable probability that use of the product will cause serious health consequences or death. With repeat offenders such as Moonlight Packing Corporation and Albertsons Companies LLC, it's clear the industry still has a long way to go in ensuring consumer safety.

## Bottom Line

The recent spate of recalls underscores the need for vigilance and transparency in the food industry. Whether it's foreign objects in dumplings or dangerously high levels of chemicals in imported goods, these incidents are reminders that food safety is everyone's business. Let's hope manufacturers, retailers, and regulators step up their game.

## A Call to Action

Don't let your pantry turn into a hazard zone. Check your shelves and stay informed. As consumers, the power to demand better lies in our hands.
